Title: A Formal Theory of Economic-Constrained Multiplanetary Transition: Dynamical Systems, Viability, and Architectural Design with Jacobian Stability, Bifurcation Analysis, and Optimal Control

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

The transition of humanity from a single-planet species to a stable multiplanetary civilization has been traditionally framed as a problem of propulsion, life support, or mission architecture. This dissertation advances a fundamentally different paradigm: multiplanetary expansion is governed by a constrained economic dynamical system in which local viability, surplus production, sequential autonomy accumulation, and institutional clarity are the binding determinants of feasibility. We formalize planetary bodies and cislunar gateways as economically coupled nodes evolving according to a system of nonlinear ordinary differential equations, where each node's state comprises its economic output rate and a continuous autonomy index representing the fraction of locally sourced mass–energy flows.

We define the viability kernel for each node as the largest subset of the state space from which trajectories can satisfy the constraints $E_i \geq C_i$ and $A_i \geq A_{\min}$ indefinitely. Economic dynamics incorporate local productivity, maintenance costs, trade spillovers attenuated by transit thresholds and institutional friction, and bounded stochastic shocks. Autonomy evolves as a logistic function of the relative surplus $(E_i - C_i)/C_i$, penalized by external dependency. Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) is modeled as a saturating productivity accelerator with diminishing returns and governance-risk penalties proportional to regulatory volatility. Institutional clarity is parameterized as an exponential modifier of transit and maintenance costs, transforming governance from a qualitative factor into a first-class economic variable.

We prove a suite of formal theorems that structure the feasibility and stability of multiplanetary transition. Theorem 1 (Necessity and Sufficiency) establishes that a stable transition from node $i$ to node $j$ is possible if and only if $i$ achieves sustained economic surplus sufficient to cover discounted transit costs and converges to an autonomy basin of attraction. Corollary 1 demonstrates the conditional instability of direct Earth–Mars expansion, which requires continuous Earth subsidy exceeding a critical threshold to avoid exponential autonomy decay. Theorem 2 characterizes the local asymptotic stability of the Earth–Moon–Mars network via the Jacobian matrix of the extended state vector, identifying diagonal dominance and bounded cross-coupling as necessary conditions to prevent failure propagation. Theorem 3 identifies a saddle-node bifurcation at a critical autonomy level $A_c = (\beta_i C_i - s)/(\alpha_i R_i)$, proving that if autonomy falls below this threshold at the moment of subsidy withdrawal, the stable equilibrium annihilates and the node exits the viability kernel irreversibly.

We further introduce a Hamiltonian action principle for the multiplanetary transition path, defining the optimal investment sequence as the control trajectory that minimizes a discounted functional penalizing state volatility and control effort. This variational framework yields a rigorous justification for the intermediate lunar node: minimizing the action functional front-loads autonomy investments on the Moon and delays Mars transit commitments until robust local stability is achieved.

The work culminates in a complete architectural design for a multiplanetary economic control system, incorporating stage-gate funding rules, feedback topologies, institutional acceleration mandates, and stochastic surplus buffers. The framework generates explicit falsifiable predictions linking observable proxies—such as the ratio of in-situ propellant production to consumption, the number of ratified space resource agreements, and the volatility of AGI deployment policy—to the probability of achieving Martian viability within a finite time horizon. All results are derived analytically and mathematically; no physical experimentation, hardware testing, or empirical data collection is performed or claimed. This dissertation provides a rigorous theoretical foundation for modeling, designing, and governing multiplanetary economic networks, shifting the discourse from technological ambition to viability-constrained systems engineering.

