7.2 Limitations of the Theoretical Framework

No theoretical framework is without boundaries. Acknowledging limitations is not an admission of weakness but a demarcation of the domain within which the theory claims validity. The following limitations are intrinsic to the model's construction and should inform its appropriate application.

7.2.1 Purely Theoretical Status

This dissertation is a work of mathematical theory. No physical experimentation, hardware prototyping, or empirical data collection has been performed. The parameters ranges presented in Chapter 5 are anchored in the 2025–2026 literature—including the global space economy's growth to $613 billion in 2024 and private space investment reaching $23.8 billion in 2026—but they have not been fitted to longitudinal data. The predictions in Section 7.1 are structured to be testable against future observations; they are not validated against historical analogs. This is appropriate for a foundational theoretical framework, but it means that the model's quantitative accuracy cannot yet be assessed.

The recent cancellation of NASA's Mars Sample Return mission—a program that had already expended nearly two decades of development effort and seen cost projections balloon to $7–11 billion before being terminated—illustrates precisely the kind of real-world complexity that our theoretical model seeks to capture but cannot fully parameterize without empirical calibration. The fact that MSR's cancellation occurred despite Perseverance having already collected and cached over 50 Martian samples demonstrates that even technically successful programs can fail when economic and institutional constraints are violated.

7.2.2 Closed-System Assumption for Earth

The model treats Earth ($i=0$) as an exogenous source with effectively infinite capacity: $E_0 \gg C_0$, $A_0 = 1$ by definition, and subsidy $s(t)$ is a control variable rather than a state constrained by terrestrial dynamics. In reality, Earth is itself a viability-constrained system. The 2026 NASA budget debates, which featured a White House proposal to cut funding by 24% to $18.8 billion versus a Senate proposal to maintain $24.9 billion, demonstrate that Earth's capacity to subsidize space activities is politically contested and fiscally constrained. Climate change, demographic shifts, resource depletion, and geopolitical instability all affect Earth's long-term capacity to serve as a source node.

Extending the model to a fully closed system where Earth's own viability kernel $\mathbb{K}_0$ is explicitly modeled would strengthen its applicability to multi-generational horizons. Such an extension would require additional state variables for terrestrial economic output, environmental constraints, and political stability—a non-trivial undertaking that lies beyond the scope of this dissertation.

7.2.3 Bounded Stochastic Representation

The stochastic term $\sigma_i \xi_i(t)$ in Equation (1) is assumed to be a mean-zero, bounded-variance disturbance. This representation captures "normal" volatility—launch delays, supply chain disruptions, moderate budget fluctuations—but it does not characterize extreme events. The cancellation of major programs, the failure of critical infrastructure (e.g., the SLS rocket, which has run approximately 140% over budget), or geopolitical shocks that sever supply chains represent "black swan" events whose probability distributions are poorly understood. The model's predictions should be interpreted as conditional on the absence of such extreme events, or as applying to the central tendency of a distribution that includes them.

7.2.4 Exclusion of Relativistic and Post-Biological Scales

The model is designed for interplanetary nodes within the inner solar system (Earth, Moon, Mars, cislunar gateways). It does not address relativistic timescales, multi-generational starships, or scenarios involving post-biological intelligence. The autonomy dynamics in Equation (2) assume human-centric life-support requirements with a thermodynamic floor $C_{\min}$ derived from current closed-loop life support benchmarks (MELiSSA, BIOS-3). Extensions to nodes requiring centuries of transit time or to non-human intelligences would require fundamentally different dynamical formulations.

7.2.5 Assumption of Rational Economic Allocation

The model assumes that economic resources are allocated rationally within the bounds defined by the parameterization. Agency problems, principal-agent conflicts, political rent-seeking, and cognitive biases are not explicitly modeled. The institutional friction parameter $\theta(t)$ partially captures the aggregate effect of these factors on costs, but it does not model their microfoundations. A more complete treatment would require integrating the present framework with public choice theory and behavioral economics.

7.2.6 Parameter Uncertainty and Sensitivity

The parameter ranges provided in Chapter 5 are theoretical envelopes, not statistically estimated confidence intervals. The sensitivity analysis in Section 5.4 identifies which parameters most strongly influence stability, but the absolute values of critical thresholds (e.g., $A_c$, $s_{\min}$) are sensitive to the specific parameter values chosen within those ranges. Future empirical work should prioritize reducing uncertainty in the highest-sensitivity parameters: autonomy convergence rate $\eta_i$, baseline productivity $\alpha_{i,0}$, and cost scaling factor $\beta_{i,0}$.

7.3 Policy Architecture

The mathematical architecture developed in this dissertation is not merely descriptive; it prescribes a control system for multiplanetary economic transition. The policy architecture derived from the stability theorems and bifurcation analysis constitutes a set of decision rules that, if implemented, would maximize the probability of remaining within the viability kernel. These rules are presented as structural implications of the model rather than as political recommendations.

7.3.1 Stage-Gate Funding with Autonomy Triggers

Policy Rule. Capital for node $j$ shall be released only when node $i$ satisfies three conditions: (1) autonomy $A_i \geq 0.65$; (2) surplus buffer $E_i - C_i \geq 1.2 \cdot C_i$; and (3) net present value of surplus covers discounted transit cost $\text{NPV}_i(T_{i \to j}) \geq T_{i \to j}(1 + \lambda_{\text{risk}})$.

Mathematical Justification. Theorem 1 establishes that these conditions are jointly necessary and sufficient for stable transition. Theorem 3 shows that failing to meet the autonomy threshold before subsidy withdrawal triggers a saddle-node bifurcation and irreversible collapse. The 20% surplus buffer (beyond the 1.0 required for $E_i \geq C_i$) provides margin against stochastic shocks $\sigma_i \xi_i(t)$.

Implementation Mechanism. Funding appropriations should be structured as viability-tied tranches rather than milestone-based payload deliveries. Current practice ties funding to discrete milestones (launch dates, hardware deliveries) rather than to continuous measures of economic health. A viability-tied approach would condition major funding increments on demonstrated surplus and autonomy metrics, analogous to the tranche structure in project finance.

Empirical Benchmark. The PwC Lunar Market Assessment projects annual lunar surface activity revenues of $127.3 billion by 2050. The stage-gate framework would require that a significant fraction of this projected revenue be realized—not merely contracted—before committing to Mars transit investments exceeding $100 billion.

7.3.2 ISRU-First Investment Mandate

Policy Rule. A minimum fraction $f_{\text{ISRU}} \in [0.4, 0.7]$ of all node investment shall be allocated to local resource utilization and closed-loop life support until $A_i \geq 0.5$.

Mathematical Justification. The autonomy dynamics (Equation 2) are driven by the relative surplus $(E_i - C_i)/C_i$. Investment in ISRU ($R_i$) increases the productivity term $\alpha_i R_i A_i$, directly accelerating autonomy growth. Investment in payload expansion without corresponding ISRU maturity increases $C_i$ without increasing $E_i$, pushing the node toward the dependency trap identified in Corollary 1.

Implementation Mechanism. Space agencies and commercial operators should establish ISRU investment accounts that are walled off from operational budgets. The Canadian Space Agency's recent $2.9 million investment in lunar ISRU prototyping and its follow-on Lunar Surface Exploration Initiative (LSEI) Architecture Studies, which explicitly target "mining and in-situ resource utilization" as a signature technology area, exemplify the kind of focused ISRU investment this rule mandates.

Resource Anchoring. Recent scientific advances have substantially reduced uncertainty about lunar water ice distribution. An Israeli-led study published in Nature Astronomy in 2026 identified the oldest and most stable cold traps at the lunar south pole, with some craters—including Haworth Crater—having remained stable for more than 3.3 billion years, providing "a roadmap for locating [ice]" and reducing costly trial-and-error exploration. Simultaneously, China's Chang'e-7 mission, scheduled for launch in 2026, will attempt the first direct search for water ice inside permanently shadowed craters using a novel "hopping" spacecraft that can access terrain inaccessible to traditional rovers. These developments reduce the resource uncertainty that might otherwise justify delaying ISRU investment.

7.3.3 Autonomy Feedback Control

Policy Rule. Policy allocation $u_i(t)$ shall be dynamically tuned to the time derivative of autonomy: $u_i(t) = u_{i,\text{base}} + K_p \max(0, -\dot{A}_i(t)) + K_d \max(0, -\ddot{A}_i(t))$, where $K_p, K_d > 0$ are proportional and derivative gains.

Mathematical Justification. The Jacobian analysis (Theorem 2) establishes that stability requires $\frac{\partial \dot{A}_i}{\partial A_i} < 0$. When $E_i < C_i$, this derivative becomes positive, signaling incipient instability. A proportional-derivative controller counteracts this tendency by increasing investment when autonomy is declining ($-\dot{A}_i > 0$) or decelerating ($-\ddot{A}_i > 0$).

Implementation Mechanism. Space agencies should establish real-time autonomy monitoring systems that track the ratio of locally sourced to total consumables, the fraction of power generated in situ, and the percentage of maintenance actions performed without Earth intervention. These metrics should feed directly into resource allocation decisions with minimal bureaucratic latency.

7.3.4 Stochastic Surplus Buffer

Policy Rule. Each node shall maintain a surplus reserve $S_{\text{reserve}, i} \geq 2 \sigma_i C_i$, where $\sigma_i$ is the estimated volatility of economic output. This buffer shall be held in liquid form and replenished during surplus periods.

Mathematical Justification. The stochastic term $\sigma_i \xi_i(t)$ in Equation (1) can push the state out of the viability kernel even if the deterministic trajectory would remain inside. For Gaussian shocks, a buffer of $2\sigma$ provides approximately 97.7% confidence of absorbing a one-standard-deviation adverse event without violating the constraint $E_i \geq C_i$.

Implementation Mechanism. The reserve should be structured as a combination of prepositioned supplies (food, water, spare parts) and Earth-based financial instruments that can be rapidly liquidated to fund emergency resupply missions. The Mars Sample Return program's cancellation due to "lack of funding" despite scientific community support illustrates the consequences of operating without adequate fiscal buffers: programs that consume their entire contingency become politically indefensible when broader budget pressures emerge.

7.3.5 AGI Governance with Variance Constraint

Policy Rule. AGI deployment policy $u_{\text{AGI}}(t)$ shall be constrained such that the rolling variance of $\text{AGI}(t)$ satisfies $\text{Var}_T(\text{AGI}) \leq \frac{\ln(1 + \delta_{\max})}{\zeta}$, where $\delta_{\max}$ is the maximum acceptable percentage increase in transit costs due to variance.

Mathematical Justification. Equation (5) shows that volatility in AGI deployment penalizes transit costs exponentially via the term $e^{\zeta \cdot \text{Var}(\text{AGI})}$. A stable, predictable regulatory environment for AGI is more important than the absolute level of AGI penetration. This finding parallels the terrestrial experience in nuclear power and biotechnology, where regulatory uncertainty has been a larger cost driver than regulatory stringency per se.

Implementation Mechanism. Space agencies and commercial operators should establish multi-year AGI deployment roadmaps with pre-announced review points and explicit criteria for modification. Regulatory changes affecting AGI in space operations should be subject to "sunrise" periods of at least three years to allow adaptation. International coordination through COPUOS or a dedicated space AI governance body could reduce the variance that arises from uncoordinated national policies.

7.3.6 Institutional Clarity as a Capital Asset

Policy Rule. A fixed fraction $g_{\text{gov}} \in [0.05, 0.15]$ of the total multiplanetary budget shall be allocated to institutional development until $\theta(t) \geq 0.7$.

Mathematical Justification. The exponential cost multiplier $C_i(t) = C_{i,0} \cdot \exp(\omega(1 - \theta(t)))$ implies that early investment in governance yields disproportionately large long-term savings. The net present value of a unit increase in $\theta$ is given by $\partial \text{NPV}/\partial \theta = \int_0^\infty e^{-\rho t} [\omega C_{i,0} e^{\omega(1-\theta)} + \zeta T_{j \to i}^0 e^{\zeta(1-\theta)}] dt$, which is large and positive for plausible parameters.

Empirical Context. The current legal landscape exhibits precisely the ambiguity that this rule seeks to reduce. The Outer Space Treaty's Article II prohibits national appropriation but is silent on private property. The Artemis Accords permit resource extraction but have been signed by only 55 nations as of early 2026 and lack universal acceptance. COPUOS's 2025 initial draft principles for space resource activities represent progress toward a multilateral framework, but the draft explicitly states that "consensus among member states" has not yet been achieved on key provisions. This ambiguity translates directly into the cost multipliers our model predicts.

Implementation Mechanism. Institutional investment should take the form of treaty negotiation support, legal framework development, dispute resolution mechanism design, and the establishment of a standing multilateral body for space resource governance. The fraction $g_{\text{gov}}$ should be treated as mandatory overhead, not discretionary spending. The Beyond Earth Symposium's 2026 conclusion that "a sustainable lunar presence requires predictable regulatory frameworks and investment confidence measured in decades, not fiscal years" aligns with this policy rule.

7.4 The Policy Trilemma

The policy architecture reveals a fundamental tension—a trilemma—that policymakers must navigate. The three objectives of (1) rapid expansion, (2) low fiscal exposure, and (3) high probability of success cannot be simultaneously maximized.

· Rapid Expansion + Low Fiscal Exposure: Pursuing rapid expansion with minimal Earth subsidy (the "commercial optimism" path) requires exceptionally high baseline productivity $\alpha_{i,0}$ and rapid autonomy convergence $\eta_i$. The Roy model of space immigration developed by Abbot and Malani (2026) finds that "getting the cost of living in space down by approximately 2 orders of magnitude is necessary to generate a space population on the order of 1 million people". If productivity falls short of this demanding threshold, the node enters the dependency trap identified in Theorem 3.
· Rapid Expansion + High Probability of Success: Pursuing rapid expansion with high success probability requires sustained Earth subsidy exceeding $s_{\min}$ (approximately $18–22 billion annually for Mars). This path consumes political capital and fiscal capacity that may not be available over multi-decade horizons, particularly given the fiscal volatility demonstrated by the 2026 NASA budget process.
· Low Fiscal Exposure + High Probability of Success: Pursuing low fiscal exposure with high success probability requires accepting slower expansion—specifically, waiting until the lunar node achieves $A_1 \geq 0.65$ before committing major resources to Mars. This path is mathematically optimal (it minimizes the action functional $\mathcal{S}$) but may conflict with geopolitical timelines and public expectations.

The resolution of this trilemma is not a mathematical question but a political one. The framework presented here clarifies the tradeoffs but does not dictate the choice. As Bhavya Lal, former NASA Associate Administrator for Technology, Policy and Strategy, observed at the 2026 Beyond Earth Symposium: "The more consequential question is not who lands first, but who brings the infrastructure—power systems, logistics chains, governance models, and commercial frameworks capable of supporting continuity. That infrastructure will determine who shapes the norms, economy, and long-term trajectory of lunar development".

7.5 Conclusion to Chapter 7

This chapter has articulated the falsifiability conditions, limitations, and policy architecture of the formal theory of economic-constrained multiplanetary transition. Four empirically testable predictions have been specified, each with explicit falsification conditions and observable proxies. The theory's limitations—including its purely theoretical status, closed-system assumption for Earth, bounded stochastic representation, exclusion of relativistic scales, assumption of rational allocation, and parameter uncertainty—have been acknowledged and circumscribed. A policy architecture comprising six structural rules has been derived from the stability theorems, culminating in the identification of a policy trilemma that frames the fundamental tradeoffs facing decision-makers.

The theory does not predict that multiplanetary transition will succeed or fail. It predicts the conditions under which success is mathematically possible. It provides a language and a structure for evaluating the economic viability of proposed architectures, for identifying the thresholds that must be crossed, and for designing control systems that maximize the probability of remaining within the viability kernel. The ultimate test of the theory lies in the alignment of its predictions with the empirical record of the coming decades. If the conditions identified here—lunar autonomy before Mars commitment, sustained surplus buffers, institutional clarity, predictable AGI governance—prove to be the binding constraints on multiplanetary expansion, the theory will have demonstrated its value. If expansion succeeds despite violating these conditions, the theory will have been productively falsified, and a better theory will be required.

In either case, the discourse will have advanced beyond the engineering optimism that has characterized it to date. A multiplanetary future, if it is to be achieved, must be achieved in full awareness of the economic dynamics that govern it. This dissertation provides the mathematical foundation for that awareness.